<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-04">
  <title>Week 4</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-hausdorff">
      <title>Separation of points</title>
      <p>
        Not all spaces are created equally. Let's briefly adopt the frame that the open neighborhoods of a point <m>x</m> in a 
        space <m>X</m> — that is, all <m>x\in U\subseteq X</m> open — form a sort of microscope: ordered by inclusion, they form 
        a microscope with which we can zoom in on <m>x</m>. Being as familiar as we are with Euclidean space and optical 
        microscopes, we would expect that given <m>y\ne x\in X</m>, we should be able to zoom in far enough so that <m>y</m> 
        leaves the frame. In fact, if we aim one microscope at <m>x</m> and another microscope at <m>y</m>, then we should be 
        able to zoom in with both so that their images do not overlap, right? Right?
      </p>
      <p>
        Alas — this is not the case. For instance, if <m>X</m> has the concrete topology, then our microscope is terrible: it 
        literally cannot zoom further than viewing all of <m>X</m> at once. More formally, we cannot find open sets 
        <m>x\inU\subseteq X</m> and <m>y\in V\subseteq X</m> for which <m>U\cap V = \varnothing</m>. When we <alert>can</alert> 
        zoom in in this fashion, we say that <m>X</m> <term>separates points</term> (or is a <term>Hausdorff space</term>).
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-separate-points">
        <title>Separates points</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A topological space <m>X</m> <term>separates points</term> (or is <term>Hausdorff</term>) :iff for all distinct 
            <m>x,y\in X</m> there exist open sets <m>x\in U\subseteq X</m> and <m>y\in V\subseteq X</m> that are disjoint 
            (<m>U\cap V=\varnothing</m>).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example>
        <title>Metric spaces are Hausdorff</title>
        <p>
          Most topology courses spend substantial time developing metric topology, but I have the sense that you have learned 
          or will soon learn this flavor of topology in analysis. Briefly, a <term>metric space</term> is a set <m>X</m> together with a <term>metric</term> 
          <m>d\colon X\times X\to \mathbb R_{\ge 0}</m> satisfying the following properties:
          <dl>
            <li>
              <title>identity of indiscernibles</title>
              <p>
                <m>d(x,y)=0</m> if and only if <m>x=y</m>,
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>symmetry</title>
              <p>
                <m>d(x,y)=d(y,x)</m> for all <m>x,y\in X</m>,
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>triangle inequality</title>
              <p>
                <m>d(x,z)\le d(x,y)+d(y,z)</m> for all <m>x,y,z\in X</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </dl>
          A metric space <m>(X,d)</m> carries a canonical topology generated by a basis of open balls
          <md>
            \mathscr B := \{B(x,r)\mid x\in X, r\gt 0\}
          </md>
          where <m>B(x,r):= \{y\in X\mid d(x,y)\lt r\}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We now demonstrate that the topology associated with a metric separates points. Let <m>x,y</m> be distinct points of 
          <m>X</m>. By identity of indiscernibles, <m>d(x,y)=R\gt 0</m>. Set <m>U = B(x,R/2),V=B(y,R/2)</m> and suppose 
          for contradiction that <m>z\in U\cap V</m>. Then, by the triangle inequality,
          <md>
            d(x,y)\le d(x,z)+d(z,y)\lt R/2+R/2=R,
          </md>
          contradicting <m>d(x,y)=R</m>, so in fact <m>U\cap V=\varnothing</m>. These sets are open neighborhoods of <m>x,y</m>, 
          respectively, in the metric topology, so the metric topology on <m>X</m> separates points.
        </p>
      </example>
      <p>
        Metric spaces provide a rich class of topologies that separate points, but we can also make som staightforward 
        constructions that fail to do so.
      </p>
      <example>
        <title>The line with two origins does not separate points</title>
        <p>
          Let <m>X</m> denote the pushout of the span <m>\mathbb R\leftarrow \mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}\to \mathbb R</m> in 
          which both maps are the usual inclusion of <m>\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}</m> into <m>\mathbb R</m>. We should think 
          of <m>X</m> as a (real) line with two origins: the quotient of <m>\mathbb R\amalg \mathbb R</m> that constructs <m>X</m> 
          identifies <m>(x,0)</m> with <m>(x,1)</m> for all <m>x\ne 0</m>, but <m>(0,0)</m> and <m>(0,1)</m> remain distinct.
        </p>
        <p>
          We claim that the pushout topology on <m>X</m> fails to separate the two origins. You will prove as much in your homework 
          via careful consideration of the canonical map <m>X\to \mathbb R</m>.
        </p>
      </example>
      <p>
        Thankfully, point separation is preserved a number of our favorite constructions.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-sep-constr">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The property of separating points is inherited by the subspace, product, and coproduct topologies.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>

    </subsubsection>
    
  </subsection>

